[[Sunlight]] is the light that apparently or observably comes from the sun in the sky. (See post #5469) 

[[Sunburst]] is for designs or figures of burst of [[sunlight]], but may not necessarily be the actual sun. (See post #645306)

title: sonic_the_hedgehog_2
body:
[b]Sonic the Hedgehog 2[/b] (not to be confused with [[Sonic The Hedgehog 2 (Film)]]) is the direct sequel to [[Sonic the Hedgehog 1]], Developed by Sonic Team and published by [[SEGA]] for the Sega Genesis [[game console]], It was released to [[Japan]] on November 21, 1991, and to the [[United States]] three days later on, November 24, 1991. 

The game follows [[Sonic the Hedgehog]] and his newly debuted sidekick Miles Prower, conveniently nicknamed [[tails (Sonic)|Tails]], adventure to gather the [[chaos emerald|Chaos Emerald's]] before [[Dr. Eggman]] can use them to power his Death Egg.

It plays like the first game, you run to the end goal as fast as you can, defeat Badnik's and collect rings to stay afloat. there are a few new mechanics though, such as the debut of the spindash, the spindash has [[Sonic The Hedgehog|Sonic]] or [[Tails (Sonic)|Tails]] curl up into a ball and rev up to go at super speeds in seconds! As well as introducing [[Super Sonic]], an ability [[Sonic The Hedgehog|Sonic]] can transform into when having all 7 [[chaos emerald|Chaos Emerald's]] and 50 rings.

h4. Trivia
* Despite being the sequel to [[Sonic the Hedgehog 1|Sonic the Hedgehog]], many believe [[Sonic CD]] to be the [i]real[/i] sequel. Sonic Origins seems to back this theory up as well.
* When initially released in [[Japan]] there were many bugs, which caused the game to be delayed for the American release.
* [[Super Sonic]] may be a homage to the [[Super Saiyan]] transformation from the [[Dragon Ball]] franchise.

h4. External Links
* "Sonic News Network: Sonic the Hedgehog 2":https://sonic.fandom.com/wiki/Sonic_the_Hedgehog

title: kawashima_sapphire
body:
Kawashima Sapphire is a character in [[Hibike! Euphonium]]. She plays the [[double bass]] in Kitauji High School's concert band, joining in the same year as [[oumae kumiko|Kumiko]]. Her bass skills are excellent, as she previously attended a private school specializing in music. Sapphire is is the name her parents gave her, but she finds that embarrassing and prefers to go by Midori (緑, first kanji of her given name).

Sapphire has [[short hair|short]] [[blonde hair]] and [[brown eyes]]. At 148 cm, she is substantially shorter than most of her peers. Sapphire is close friends with [[Katou Hazuki]].

title: nt-d
body:
Abbreviation for [b]N[/b]ew[b]t[/b]ype [b]D[/b]rive, but also regarded as [b]N[/b]ew[b]t[/b]ype [b]D[/b]estroyer (due to [[Full Frontal]] quoting it as such), it is the fully-activated mode of the [[Unicorn Gundam]].

When in use, the Unicorn Gundam's armor slides open, revealing its glowing red [[Psycho Frame]], then its single horn at its head splits into the well-known V shaped crest. It activates when there is an entity that is regarded as Newtype by the system, or when the pilot's Newtype power grows, activated at will. In this mode, the Unicorn Gundam's performance increases drastically and gains the ability to hijack an enemy's [[funnels (gundam)|]] or bits if there are any.

The psycho frame can also be depicted as grey (deactivated), gold (on the [[Unicorn Gundam Banshee]]), blue (on the [[Unicorn Gundam Phenex]] and [[Unicorn Gundam Perfectibility]]) or green (if the pilot's Newtype abilities is fully awakened).

[spoiler] The green NT-D features new abilities such as replicating the Axis Shock, previously done by the [[Nu Gundam]], and the ability to remotely manipulate weapons equipped with psycho frame, even if said weapon has no thrusters (in this case, the Shield Funnels equipped onto the Unicorn Gundam and Unicorn Gundam Phenex).

title: full_armor_unicorn_gundam
body:
The heavily armed upgrade of the [[unicorn_gundam|RX-0 Unicorn Gundam]]. It is piloted by [[Banagher Links]].

The Full Armor Mode was an enhancement plan devised by [[Irei Takuya]] while aboard the Nahel Argama and is based on Takuya's extensive knowledge of mobile suits. After Banagher's Newtype potential manifests itself, the [[Psycho Frame]] changes color to a vibrant green. Unlike other mobile suits with the Full Armor designation, the FA Unicorn does not consist of any additional armor for the MS frame itself (except extra [[shield|shields]]). However it does introduce a large array of weapons, which are added to the legs, backpack and forearms.

At first glance, what appears to be a haphazard collection of weaponry is actually a superbly balanced set-up which draws out the maximum combat potential of the Unicorn. The new array of weapons includes two backpack-mounted hyper bazookas, numerous hand grenades and grenade launchers, missile pods, forearm-mounted Gatling guns, and two additional I-field-equipped shields, one on the backpack and the other on the right forearm. The backpack also features two massive vernier-boosters taken from a [[base_jabber|Base Jabber Type 94]] to compensate for the increased mass, with one of the additional shields situated between them. The unit's entire weapons load can be disconnected at any time if the ammunitions are completely spent to avoid becoming dead-weight. Like the normal Unicorn, the Full Armor Unicorn can take control of an enemy's psycommu weapons, even Quasi-Psycommu bits, when the [[NT-D]] is activated.

Just like the original Unicorn, its Full Armor version is designed in real life by [[Katoki Hajime]].

title: fin_funnels
body:
A form of remote weapon unique to the [[Nu Gundam]]/[[Hi-Nu Gundam]] (and retroactively, its testbed unit, the [[Delta Gundam Kai]]). Despite their name, the fin funnels equipped on Nu Gundam/Hi-Nu Gundam are in function "[[bit (gundam)|bits]]", since they have built-in generators rather than the E-caps used by [[funnels (gundam)|]]. While this made them much more expensive to construct, and allowed less modules to be equipped than the standard, this had the enormous benefit of giving the fin funnels a tremendously long operational time. Circling the battlefield on their own, the fin funnels could be utilized in far more creative and strategic ways than standard funnels.

The actual beam fired by the fin funnels was also more powerful, given that they are emitted by a generator instead of an E-cap, allowing for better performance compared to Zeon's funnels. The fin funnels also had the ability to generate a unique beam shield, known as a "fin funnel barrier", to provide a defense against both beam weaponry and solid projectiles with lower outputs compared to the beam shield's power consumption. Although these unique funnels proved incredibly effective and flexible in purpose, they were also much larger than the standard funnel, making them easier targets to shoot down. With the help of the [[Psycho Frame]] technology, Nu Gundam/Hi-Nu Gundam pilot [[Amuro Ray]] can utilize these fin funnels more effectively by thoughts alone.

It should be noted that the Hi-Nu Gundam is capable of recharging and refueling its fin funnels, thanks to the upgrades on its backpack.

This tag can also refer to fin-shaped remote weapons or those that physically resemble the Nu Gundam/Hi-Nu Gundam's fin funnels.

title: hi-nu_gundam
body:
Japanese: Hi-νガンダム

The alternate interpretation of the [[Nu Gundam]] featured in  [[char's_counterattack_-_beltorchika's_children|Mobile Suit Gundam: Char's Counterattack - Beltorchika's Children]].

In addition to a more bulky design, the RX-93-ν2 Hi-Nu Gundam sports an exclusively white and purple (or blue) color scheme to distinguish it from the white and black (or midnight blue) paint job on the RX-93 Nu Gundam. Like the Nu Gundam, the Hi-Nu Gundam also has a mouthpiece with three vents. 

The most prolific difference, however, is its distinct back boosters and revised [[fin funnels|fin funnel]] system. The fairly standard backpack design of the Nu Gundam is replaced with a much more unique dual "long booster" system, with another long booster situated between them and two propellant tanks angled below the dual long boosters. These boosters were capable of great accelerations, and the propellant tanks extended the duration of time the boosters could remain active. The long boosters also served as the storage area for the unit's fin funnels. Also, unlike the Nu Gundam, the Hi-Nu Gundam could recharge the fin funnel's power supply, extending their performance time.

Apart from the obvious visual differences, the Hi-Nu Gundam also expands on the Nu Gundam's armaments, with the addition of a powerful [[machine gun]] in its right forearm as well as the inclusion of an extra [[energy sword|beam saber]], bringing the number of beam sabers up to three. The suit can also use a Hyper Mega Bazooka Launcher, an improved model of the weapon used by the [[Hyaku Shiki]] during the [[zeta gundam|Gryps Conflict]], when heavier firepower is required.

Thanks to its [[Psycho Frame]], a vast improvement over the psycommu system prevalent among mobile suits designed to be used by Newtype pilots, the Hi-Nu Gundam's pilot had much greater control over the mobile suit, piloting it almost as if it were an extension of his own body and bringing out the suit's fullest performance.

It is piloted and designed in-universe by [[Amuro Ray]]. In real life, it is designed by [[Izubuchi Yutaka]].

title: psycho_frame
body:
Appearing in the Universal Century timeline of the [[Gundam]] franchise, the [b]Psycho Frame[/b] is a technology that builds on the brainwave-to-machine code translator known as [I]Psycommu[/I] into the atom-level of the metal frame of a [[Mobile Suit]]. More specifically, the psycommu chips are shrank and lined in the gaps between the hive-shaped metal particles of the mobile suit's frame. This allows a Newtype pilot to control the mobile suit as if it were their own body with limitations. Traditional psycommu systems require a large subsystem, and are typically mounted on larger Mobile Armor platforms. With the development of the Psycho Frame, it became possible to install a psycommu system into a smaller mobile suit.

Psycho Frame materials physically appears to be [[glowing]] (usually emitting green-colored light) and comes in various shapes and sizes, from a small sample (one is seen to be T-shaped and always carried by [[Chan Agi]] for study), to being lined to the entire mobile suit's frame (as seen on [[Unicorn Gundam]] units).

title: kazakhstan
body:
A country in Central Asia. It is the world's largest landlocked country, and the ninth-largest in the world; its territory of 2,727,300 square kilometres (1,053,000 sq mi) is larger than Western Europe. It is neighbored clockwise from the north by [[Russia]], [[China]], Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan, and also borders on a large part of the Caspian Sea. 

The terrain of Kazakhstan includes flatlands, steppe, taiga, rock canyons, hills, deltas, snow-capped mountains, and deserts. With 16.6 million people (2011 estimate) Kazakhstan has the 62nd largest population in the world, though its population density is less than 6 people per square kilometre (15 per sq. mi.). The capital is the city of [i]Astana[/i].

Notably appears as the starting country in the [[Strider (video game)|]] [[Science fiction]] [[video game]] from the 80s, where in its first levels it is referred to as [b]Kazakh[/b].

title: conservatory
body:
A conservatory is normally characterized by the following:

* A building largely made up out of framing and glass panels.
* A building that has been made with an eye for design or looks.
* A building which main purpose is as a living / activity space for people.
* A building that is often (but not always) attached to a house or other type of building.
* A building that has a glass roof and one or more glass wall.
* A building that often has plants but also has other objects like furniture (that looks like it is supposed to be there).
* A building used for things like enjoying the sun wile isolated for the cold outside air.

This is in contrast with a [[greenhouse]], a building that is often confused with a conservatory as the main purpose of a greenhouse is the growing of and the caring for plants.

A few examples for a conservatory are the following:

* A swimming pool with a glass roof and wall(s).
* A room in a house or attached to a house with furniture for seating and more which may also have some plants.
* A free-standing building in a garden like you sometimes see in anime or high society series where they are drinking tea. 
* A botanical garden can also be called a conservatory although it often overlaps with a greenhouse.

title: clare_(claymore)
body:
The main protagonist of [[Claymore (series)|]].

In the beginning of the series, Clare is the number 47 of [i]The Organization[/i]'s 78th generation, making her the lowest ranked claymore. She also holds the distinction of becoming the first individual to willingly become a claymore (half-human, half-youma female warriors). Her goal is revenge against the awakened being [[priscilla_(claymore)|Priscilla]]. When first introduced, Clare was a very cold warrior who prioritized her duties over everything else, however, she saves [[raki_(claymore)|Raki]] from a youma and takes him under her care because he reminds her of herself when she was younger.

Clare has [[short_hair|short]] [[blonde hair]] with [[bangs]]  and [[grey eyes]]. Her usual outfit consists of [[white bodysuit]], large [[pauldrons]], leather [[vambraces]], [[faulds]] and [[armored boots]]. In the series, Clare is frequently seen wielding a [[claymore_(sword)|]].

title: tio_plato
body:
English: Tio Plato
Japanese: ティオ・プラトー (tio puratou)
Age: 14 ([[zero_no_kiseki|zero]]/[[ao_no_kiseki|ao]]), 16 ([[sen_no_kiseki_iii|sen 3]])

Main character of [[Eiyuu Densetsu]]'s [[zero_no_kiseki|Zero]]/[[Ao no Kiseki]] duology. [[Mishy]] fangirl.

Has an in-game nickname ティオすけ (tiosuke) given her by [[Randolph Orlando]] and adopted by fans. Translated as Tio Tot.

[tn]ティオすけ is a pun on combining ティオ + ちび助. ちび助 (chibisuke, usually written using kana alone) literally means young child, pipsqueak. So meaning of this nickname can be understood as tiny/little Tio.[/tn]
[tn][b]Tio Tot[/b] translation was first introduced by Geofront fan-translation team in [[Zero  no Kiseki]]. Later in [[Sen no Kiseki III]] it was adopted as an official translation.[/tn]
[tn]There is also exists [b]Petiote[/b] variant of translating this nickname, it was found in Guren's fan-translation of [[zero_no_kiseki|Zero]] and [[Ao no Kiseki]]. Petiote is a french slang name for little girl, which is also works as a pun on petite + Tio.[/tn]

Element: Light
Style: Attack
Age: 34
Height: 205 cm
CV: [[Terasoma Masaki]]

Geisenborger is a [[Draph]] mercenary who lives for the sake of battle. He throws himself into the heart of wars indiscriminately, relishing in battle wherever he goes. A proud warrior in heart and mind, Geisenborger will readily compare any circumstance to a sort of battlefield, even the most mundane things, which often leaves him gravely embarrassed in the aftermath.

[spoiler]During an encounter that left him on the verge of death, a singular prayer caused him to form a pact with [[The Star (Granblue Fantasy)|The Star]], who heard his silent prayer beneath the night skies, and granted him new strength. However, this caused Geisenborger to lose his sense of pain entirely, causing him untold frustration and leaving him despising The Star. Even after his pact is later renewed, under his conditions, he still does not view The Star favorably at all.[/spoiler]

h4. External Links

* "Granblue Fantasy Wiki: Geisenborger":https://gbf.wiki/Geisenborger

title: adam_jensen
body:
The main protagonist in the third game of the [[Deus Ex]] [[cyberpunk]] [[video game]] series, [[Deus Ex: Human Revolution]] (2011). Also appears in its sequel, [[Deus Ex: Mankind Divided]] (2016).

[b]Adam Jensen[/b] is a biomechanical [[cyborg]] in the year 2027. 

He is a man with short spiky brown hair and a [[goatee]], who usually wears a dark [[coat]]. Adam works as security chief in a private cyborg development company.

His look was inspired by [[Molly Millions]] from the 80s [[science fiction]] novel [[Neuromancer]].

title: veilside
body:
A Japanese [[car]] aftermarket company, known for producing extreme body kits and other customization parts. 

Veilside is most well known for their [[Mazda RX-7 FD|FD RX-7]] "Fortune":[http://www.veilsidejpn.com/en/rx7_fortune.php] body kit, which was featured in [[The Fast and The Furious: Tokyo Drift]]. Other notable Veilside kits include the "4059GTR":[http://www.veilsidejpn.com/en/4509gtr.php] kit for the [[toyota supra mk iv|Mk IV Supra]] and their assorted [[Nissan Fairlady Z|Fairlady Z]] kits, particularly for the [[Nissan 350Z|350]] and [[Nissan 370Z|370]].

title: deus_ex:_human_revolution

The Shouryuuken is, along with the [[Hadouken]], the signature move of [[Ryu (street fighter)|Ryu]] and [[Ken Masters|Ken]], and over the course of the series multiple other characters with various degrees of association with them have also been introduced as users of the technique.

h4. Variants

* [[Shin Shouryuuken]] (真・昇龍拳)
* Metsu Shouryuuken (滅・昇龍拳)
* Shouryuu Reppa (昇龍裂破)
* Shinryuuken (神龍拳)
* Gou Shouryuuken (豪昇龍拳)
* Messatsu Gou Shouryuu (滅殺豪昇龍)

title: pansy
body:
A popular, decorative garden flower hybridized from [i]Viola tricolor[/i] with other [i]Viola[/i] species.  Popular for use in [[flower bed|flower beds]].

Pansies come in practically every color of the rainbow.  Pansies have a very distinctive flower with five petals, arranged with three petals on top, usually with a dark lobe pattern in the center that combines to give the impression of a butterfly.  

This center, darkened pattern is generally how you tell pansies from [[violet_(flower)|violets]] and other [i]Viola[/i] species.

title: uta_no_prince-sama
body:
A Japanese multimedia franchise about male idols by [i]Broccoli[/i], originally starting with an otome game published in 2010 and since then has spawned multiple sequels and rhythm game spin-offs, with the most notable being [[Uta no Prince-sama: Shining Live]]. It has since received a manga and a 2011 anime with a second season in 2012, a third in 2014, a fourth in 2016, and a movie in 2019. 
It is considered one of the foremost franchises in the male [[idol]] genre and has retained its fame both in Japan and worldwide for more than a decade. 

The original plot line followed the heroine [[Nanami Haruka]]’s life in Saotome Academy, a prestigious performing arts school made up of students who are either vying to become an idol or a music producer, as she chases after her dream of becoming a composer and someday writing a song for her favorite idol HAYATO. Haruka becomes acquainted with six of her classmates, who are all competing to become idols. For her project, she must team up with another student as an idol-producer team, and if they are successful, they will join Shining Agency after graduation.  

The franchise features three idol groups: the main group [[STARISH|ST★RISH]], [[QUARTET NIGHT]] - a band made up of the seniors of ST★RISH in the 2013 game [i]Uta no Prince-sama: All Star[/i], and HE★VENS - an anime-only idol group introduced in [[uta_no_prince-sama_maji_love_2000_percent|Uta no Prince-sama: Maji Love 2000%]] and not seen before in the games who become rivals to ST★RISH

title: jeff_the_killer
body:
One of the earliest and most iconic [[creepypasta]] characters.

The original image of Jeff associated with the story is a photoshopped image of a video still of a middle-aged Asian woman approaching the camera, at which point her face appeared quite white - the photoshop embellished the whiteness of her face further, among other things, becoming the iconic image. It was spread around the Japanese Internet, 2ch in particular, as a surprise/shock image before making its way to the English-speaking Internet. May have some connection to [[Kuchisake-onna]].

In late 2022 and early 2023, as part of the trend of [[AI-generated art (topic)|]] using img2img to create pareidolia-inducing images, several creepypasta images, such as Jeff's, would be inserted to create cute anime girls, to be shared around and cause mental damage to those who look upon them. These AI anime girls in turn have inspired fanart of their own, including those based on [[jeff the killer (ai-gen)|Jeff]].

title: toki_(hokuto_no_ken)
body:
[b]Toki[/b] is the second of the four Hokuto brothers from [[Hokuto no Ken]]. He is a pacifist who seeks to use Hokuto Shinken as a healing art. Toki's self-made technique, Hokuto Ujou Ken (北斗有情拳, "North Star Humane Fist"), is an art that is capable of healing or destroying that which it is used on. When fatally wounded with this style, the dying experiences a great feeling of euphoria, instead of horrifying pain. 

Toki is from the Land of Asura, and along with [[raoh (hokuto no ken)|Raoh]], is orphaned and adopted by Ryuken, who is seeking a student to train. Although he originally doesn't train Toki, Toki shows incredible potential, and he is made to promise that he will stop Raoh if he falls down the wrong path.

During The Nuclear fallout, Toki suffered from radiation after volunteered himself to close the shelter's door (which can only be closed from outside i.e. a plot device), thus limited his power usage, since it will slowly draining his life power out.

h4. Known moves

* 北斗有情破顔拳 ([i][[Hokuto Ujou Hagan Ken]][/i])
** A humane technique where aura blasts fired from the forearms go in two separate directions and make the opponent(s) explode without feeling any pain.

* 北斗有情断迅拳 ([i]Hokuto Ujou Danjin Ken[/i])
** A humane technique that causes multiple opponents' heads to be split without making them feel any pain.

* 闘勁呼法 ([i]Tokei Kohou[/i])
** A secret technique which sends a shockwave through the ground.

* 天翔百裂拳 ([i]Tenshou Hyakuretsu Ken[/i])
** Toki's airborne version of the [i]Hokuto Hyakuretsu Ken[/i].

title: mahjong_tile
body:
A thick, blocky tile used in the game of [[mahjong]]. Mahjong tiles are traditionally made of bamboo and bone, although most modern tiles are made of plastic.

A mahjong set usually consists of 144 tiles. They are:
* 108 suited tiles. There are three suits, each numbered 1 to 9 with four tiles each number, thus 36 per suit:
** Circles
** Bamboos (1 Bamboo actually has a bird pictured to deter cheating by adding more bamboo lines)
** Characters (Chinese numerals with 萬, [i]man[/i]/[i]wan[/i] written on the lower part)
* 28 honor tiles that are suitless:
** 16 Wind tiles, four each for North (北), South (南), East (東), and West (西).
** 12 Dragon tiles, with four tiles for each "color":
*** Red Dragon, symbolized by a red 中
*** Green Dragon, symbolized by a green 發
*** White Dragon, which is blank in Japanese sets (Some other sets have White Dragon tiles with a decorative blue rectangle on each to distinguish them from replacement tiles.)
* 8 optional "flower" tiles, so called because they are often depicted with flowers (many sets have them, but some including Japanese sets don't):
** 4 tiles representing actual flowers: plum (梅), orchid (蘭), chrysanthemum (菊), and bamboo (竹)
** 4 tiles representing seasons: spring (春), summer (夏), autumn (秋), and winter (冬)

title: kinnikuman
body:
Manga series created by Yoshinori Nakai and Takashi Shimada under the name Yudetamago. Originally serialized in [i]Weekly Shounen Jump[/i] from 28 May 1979 to March 1987 for 387 chapters and later collected in 36 volumes. It was adapted into two anime series: a 137-episode series that aired on NTV from 3 April 1983 to 1 October 1986, and a 46-episode series ([i]Kinnikuman: Scramble for the Throne[/i]) that also aired on NTV from 6 October 1991 to 27 September 1992, in addition to seven theatrical films (1984-1986) and a television special (7 April 1984).

After 24 years, it returned in [i]Shuu Play News[/i], Shueisha's web version of [i]Weekly Playboy[/i] on 28 November 2011. An additional 22 volumes have been published, numbered 37 to 58 as of 3 March 2017.

The series involves an intergalactic stand-off between various heroes and villains with [[wrestling]] as a center theme.
